ğŸ”¹ Real-Time Company Example â€“ Naming Convention
In companies, DevOps engineers must follow strict naming conventions for resources.
For example:

ğŸ‘‰ EC2 instances, S3 buckets, RDS databases, and IAM roles must follow the format:

<company>-<app>-<environment>-<region>-<resource>
Manually repeating this format everywhere is painful âŒ and prone to mistakes.
Thatâ€™s where locals help âœ….

Example Terraform Code
# locals.tf
locals {
  company     = "acme"
  app_name    = "payments"
  environment = "prod"
  region      = "us-east-1"

  # Standard naming convention
  common_name = "${local.company}-${local.app_name}-${local.environment}-${local.region}"
}

# EC2 Instance
resource "aws_instance" "app_server" {
  ami           = "ami-123456"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"

  tags = {
    Name = "${local.common_name}-ec2"
  }
}

# S3 Bucket
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "app_data" {
  bucket = "${local.common_name}-s3"
}

# IAM Role
resource "aws_iam_role" "app_role" {
  name = "${local.common_name}-role"

  assume_role_policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17",
    Statement = [
      {
        Effect = "Allow",
        Principal = { Service = "ec2.amazonaws.com" },
        Action = "sts:AssumeRole"
      }
    ]
  })
}
âœ… What Happens Here?
locals.common_name = "acme-payments-prod-us-east-1"

EC2 instance tag â†’ acme-payments-prod-us-east-1-ec2

S3 bucket name â†’ acme-payments-prod-us-east-1-s3

IAM role â†’ acme-payments-prod-us-east-1-role

ğŸ”¹ Why is this powerful?
Consistency â†’ All resources follow the same naming format.

Easy Updates â†’ If tomorrow environment changes from prod â†’ dev, you change it once in locals and all resources are updated.

Avoid Mistakes â†’ No chance of typos since youâ€™re not repeating values everywhere.

Scalable â†’ Works for 10 resources or 1000 resources the same way.

ğŸ‘‰ This is exactly how many companies maintain clean, reusable, production-ready Terraform code.

